Yes ✅ — it will pass if send_email is actually called.

But let’s understand exactly why, because this is important.

Your code:
expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

If inside PaymentProcessor#call you have:

NotificationService.send_email(user)

Then:

✔ RSpec intercepts the method
✔ Tracks whether it was called
✔ Since it was called → test passes

🧠 What Actually Happens Internally

When you write:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

RSpec:

Replaces the real send_email method temporarily

Sets an expectation that it must be called once

If it is not called → test fails

So yes — your test passes because it was called.

⚠️ Important Detail (Interview-Level)

If send_email is NOT called:

class PaymentProcessor
  def call(user)
    # forgot to call NotificationService
  end
end

Then test fails with something like:

expected NotificationService to receive :send_email but it did not
⚠️ Another Important Detail

If method is called MORE than once:

It will also fail unless you specify:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email).twice

By default, RSpec expects it exactly once.

🔥 One More Important Concept

When you use:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

It automatically stubs the method too.

That means:

The real implementation will NOT run

Unless you use .and_call_original

Example:

expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email).and_call_original

Now it will both:

Expect it

Run real method

🎯 Final Answer to Your Question

“Above expect line will hit true because it’s called?”

Yes ✅
It passes because RSpec expected that method call and the method was indeed called.

